    46→ * {@link RecordBatch} implementation for Kafka record format magic version 2 and above.
    47→ *
    48→ * <p><strong>Binary Format:</strong> This class implements the following record batch schema:
    49→ * <pre>{@code
    50→ * RecordBatch =>
    51→ *  BaseOffset => Int64              # First offset in this batch
    52→ *  Length => Int32                  # Size of batch data following the length field
    53→ *  PartitionLeaderEpoch => Int32    # Leader epoch at time of batch write
    54→ *  Magic => Int8                    # Record format version (2+)
    55→ *  CRC => Uint32                    # CRC-32C checksum (covers Attributes onward)
    56→ *  Attributes => Int16              # Batch attributes (compression, transactional, etc.)
    57→ *  LastOffsetDelta => Int32         # Offset of last record relative to BaseOffset
    58→ *  BaseTimestamp => Int64           # Timestamp of first record (or delete horizon)
    59→ *  MaxTimestamp => Int64            # Maximum timestamp in batch
    60→ *  ProducerId => Int64              # Producer ID for idempotency/transactions
    61→ *  ProducerEpoch => Int16           # Producer epoch for idempotency/transactions
    62→ *  BaseSequence => Int32            # Sequence number of first record
    63→ *  RecordsCount => Int32            # Number of records in batch
    64→ *  Records => [Record]              # Compressed or uncompressed record data
    65→ * }</pre>
    66→ *
    67→ * <p><strong>Checksum Computation:</strong> The CRC field uses the CRC-32C (Castagnoli) polynomial and covers
    68→ * all data from the Attributes field through the end of the batch. The PartitionLeaderEpoch field is intentionally
    69→ * excluded from the CRC to avoid recomputation whenever a broker assigns a new leader epoch.
    70→ *
    71→ * <p><strong>Compression:</strong> When the batch has a compression codec enabled (see Attributes), the record data
    72→ * immediately following the RecordsCount field is compressed as a unit using the specified codec.
    73→ *
    74→ * <p><strong>Log Compaction Behavior:</strong> Unlike older record formats, magic v2+ batches preserve the
    75→ * BaseOffset, BaseSequence, and LastSequence from the original batch even after log compaction. This is critical
    76→ * for correctness:
    77→ * <ul>
    78→ *   <li>Preserving sequence numbers prevents duplicate detection errors after broker failover</li>
    79→ *   <li>If all records are removed during compaction, an empty batch header is retained to preserve producer state</li>
    80→ *   <li>BaseTimestamp reflects the timestamp of the first record (or delete horizon if set)</li>
    81→ *   <li>MaxTimestamp is preserved for LOG_APPEND_TIME or empty batches; reset for CREATE_TIME</li>
    82→ *   <li>Empty batches are retained until a new sequence is written or the producer ID is expired</li>
    83→ * </ul>
    84→ *
    85→ * <p><strong>Attributes Field:</strong> The 16-bit attributes field encodes multiple flags:
    86→ * <pre>{@code
    87→ * Bits 0-2:   Compression codec (0=none, 1=gzip, 2=snappy, 3=lz4, 4=zstd)
    88→ * Bit 3:      Timestamp type (0=CREATE_TIME, 1=LOG_APPEND_TIME)
